'https://github.com/Azure/azure-sdk-for-java/pull/28360.diff', 'patch_url': 'https://github.com/Azure/azure-sdk-for-java/pull/28360.patch', 'merged_at': None}, 'body': "# Description

Updates `SwaggerMethodParser` and related classes to pre-compute values that are known during initialization instead of computing them on each request. The following values were made pre-computed:

- Eagerly reading response
- Strongly-typed headers type
- Return entity type
- Wire response type
- Return type decodable

All values are based on information from the `Method` that is passed into `SwaggerMethodParser` during construction. These values don't change during runtime and can be pre-computed.

As part of this change `HttpResponseDecodedData` now exposes new getters which are overridden by `SwaggerMethodParser` to return the pre-computed values. To support `HttpResponseDecodedData`'s default interface implementations, logic for getting the pre-computed values has been moved to utility methods in `TypeUtils`, and both the default implementation and pre-computed values call into these methods to get the value.

Description

Adds miscellaneous performance and reliability improvements to azure-core.

- Updated `AddDatePolicy` to use optimized RFC1123 string creation. Falls back to previous functionality if an error occurs (unlikely).
- Updated HTTP request and response body logging to use low-copy APIs introduced recently.
- Added cache for previously used `HttpResponseException` constructors instead of looking it up each time the exception occurs. Additionally, added specific checks for `HttpResponseException` types that exist in azure-core to reduce the usage of reflection when constructing exceptions.
- Added properties to `SwaggerMethodParser` to track the index of `Context` and `RequestOptions` in the parameters array passed instead of looking it up on each call.

# All SDK Contribution checklist:
- [x] **The pull request does not introduce [breaking changes]**
- [x] **CHANGELOG is updated for new features, bug fixes or other significant changes.**
- [x] **I have read the [contribution guidelines](https://github.com/Azure/azure-sdk-for-java/blob/main/CONTRIBUTING.md).**

## [General Guidelines and Best Practices](https://github.com/Azure/azure-sdk-for-java/blob/main/CONTRIBUTING.md#developer-guide)
- [x] Title of the pull request is clear and informative.
- [x] There are a small number of commits, each of which have an informative message. This means that previously merged commits do not appear in the history of the PR. For more information on cleaning up the commits in your PR, [see this page](https://github.com/Azure/azure-powershell/blob/master/documentation/development-docs/cleaning-up-commits.md).

### [Testing Guidelines](https://github.com/Azure/azure-sdk-for-java/blob/main/CONTRIBUTING.md#building-and-unit-testing)
- [x] Pull request includes test coverage for the included changes.

As of the day of creation of this ticket, we have a limited document on deprecation - Link - https://github.com/Azure/azure-sdk-for-java/wiki/Deprecation 
Where the stated goal is to never release a client library that is breaking, except in certain pre-agreed releases.

This leaves a gap when it comes to other information like 

- What are the release guidelines for releasing such a breaking change?
- What would the timeline be for such a release?
- What are the places where this should be documented - JavaDoc, Samples ?
- What communication mediums will be used to send out the information on the release to customers - blog posts, tweets?
- What will our support strategy be for customers using the deprecated API?

***Why is this not a Bug or a feature Request?***
This issue is to track a gap in our change process, which is not a bug or a feature

 **Information Checklist**
 Kindly make sure that you have added all the following information above and checkoff the required fields otherwise we will treat the issuer as an incomplete report
- [x] Query Added
- [x] Setup information Added - N/A

Description

@schaabs noted that there are potential cases where the wrong credentials might be created given a set of environment variables. This PR adds tests to validate that. It also fixes one case where it was wrong - we would try IMDS instead of AppService when `IDENTITY_ENDPOINT` and `IDENTITY_HEADER` were set, but not `IDENTITY_SERVER_THUMBPRINT`.

@schaabs noted that there are potential cases where the wrong credentials might be created given a set of environment variables. This PR adds tests to validate that. It also fixes one case where it was wrong - we would try IMDS instead of AppService when `IDENTITY_ENDPOINT` and `IDENTITY_HEADER` were set, but not `IDENTITY_SERVER_THUMBPRINT`.

'body': '# Description

This PR is a prototype on removing the usage of Jackson Databind in `azure-identity`. It replaces instances of `ObjectMapper` and usage of `JacksonAdapter` with `JsonFactory`, `JsonGenerator`, and `JsonParser` and handwriting serialization and deserialization logic.

All SDK Contribution checklist:
- [ ] **The pull request does not introduce [breaking changes]**
- [ ] **CHANGELOG is updated for new features, bug fixes or other significant changes.**
- [ ] **I have read the [contribution guidelines](https://github.com/Azure/azure-sdk-for-java/blob/main/CONTRIBUTING.md).**

## [General Guidelines and Best Practices](https://github.com/Azure/azure-sdk-for-java/blob/main/CONTRIBUTING.md#developer-guide)
- [ ] Title of the pull request is clear and informative.
- [ ] There are a small number of commits, each of which have an informative message. This means that previously merged commits do not appear in the history of the PR. For more information on cleaning up the commits in your PR, [see this page](https://github.com/Azure/azure-powershell/blob/master/documentation/development-docs/cleaning-up-commits.md).

### [Testing Guidelines](https://github.com/Azure/azure-sdk-for-java/blob/main/CONTRIBUTING.md#building-and-unit-testing)
- [ ] Pull request includes test coverage for the included changes.

'2022-03-07T20:17:27Z', 'closed_at': None, 'author_association': 'MEMBER', 'active_lock_reason': None, 'body': '## The problem: unrecovered receiver(s)

[Here](https://github.com/Azure/azure-sdk-for-java/files/8194575/User_Log.xlsx) is the SDK log from a user, experiencing the stopping of one or more partition receivers. The only option was to recover by restarting the pod. Similar incident happened a few times. The log is for one such incident where only 1 out of 4 partitions recovered after a servicing event, and the rest 3 stopped without notifying the application.

_The log file contains the log entries in descending order of timestamp - i.e. the first logline in the file is the latest. Colors are applied to sets of related consecutive loglines to make it easy for human eyes to parse._

The logs show that certain endpoints-closing traffic initiated by the service resulted in SDK entering an unrecoverable state. The design of SDK is to recover from endpoints-closing traffic unless it is associated with a catastrophic event (such as extended service downtime, user network downtime). There is no consistent repro given the service traffic drives it, and NOT ALL closure traffic cause this.

## The problematic service traffic: endpoint-closure events

The following are the SDK internal events in response to endpoint-closure traffic, extracted from the log -

## Reproducing the endpoint-closure traffic events

Since all these SDK events are initiated by the service traffic and notified by the 3rd party ProtonJ library, there is no easy way to produce the same traffic in the same order with similar timing.

Given the limited options, we modified the library code to inject these ProtonJ events in the same order (as appears in the Cx log) with similar delays between events. Approximately 8 out of 10 runs produced the local log that matches with the user logs.

The repro has 3 steps -

1. Create EH with 4 partitions. Keep the EH empty to ensure service is not interfering with event injection (step 3).
2. Run a simple code to connect to 4 partitions using low-level receiver client. Let SDK to open endpoints as usual - connection, sessions, and links to the service. Use the modified library code to cache the ProtonJ objects representing these endpoints and handlers.
3. Use the cached ProtonJ objects to inject the events that otherwise would have been produced in response to real service closure traffic. SDK seems to recover if following conditions are not met -
    - The ordering of events must match.
    - The "timing" (delay) between events must match.

The produced local logs match the user log - including all the exceptions, associated stack trace, and other flow-related logs in the correct logical order. An instance of such a locally produced log is [here](https://github.com/Azure/azure-sdk-for-java/files/8194609/Local_Log.md).

## Root causing

1. All 3 (out of 4) unrecovered receivers had a similar pattern. Hence focused on one of the unrecovered receivers, the partition 1 receiver.
2. Within the async state machine, identified the subgraph representing the recovery flow of partition 1 receiver.
3. Modified the subgraph's reactor-chain to log reactor terminal event - completion and error.
4. Looked for hanging nodes in the subgraph instance i.e., points in the reactor-chain where the a terminal event didn't emit.

It was observed that [this](https://github.com/Azure/azure-sdk-for-java/blob/400f6198aaf1258ec0b57a2bebc59ff9e7ac81ae/sdk/core/azure-core-amqp/src/main/java/com/azure/core/amqp/implementation/ReactorSession.java#L373) reactive `authroize()` node never terminated i.e., it didn't emit a completion or error terminal signal.

### Confirming the observation

To confirm this is really the problematic node (or root-node of sub-subgraph with the problem), a "timeout" operator is applied after the `authorize` node, which, when expired, unblocked the node in the subgraph that inturns unblocked the recovery path of partition 1 receiver (same for the other two receivers with the similar symptom).

### Digging further down in the subgraph (part 1)

Applying the "timeout" for a node close to the IO makes sense. But it is crucial to understand the network (or any IO) is the immediate bottleneck here.

Hence, continued drilling down the subgraph rooted at `authorize()` and reached this terminal [Sink node](https://github.com/Azure/azure-sdk-for-java/blob/400f6198aaf1258ec0b57a2bebc59ff9e7ac81ae/sdk/core/azure-core-amqp/src/main/java/com/azure/core/amqp/implementation/RequestResponseChannel.java#L320) in RequestResponseChannel::sendWithAck method, and identified that this Sink is never terminated.

The RRChannel tracks the Sink in question [here](https://github.com/Azure/azure-sdk-for-java/blob/400f6198aaf1258ec0b57a2bebc59ff9e7ac81ae/sdk/core/azure-core-amqp/src/main/java/com/azure/core/amqp/implementation/RequestResponseChannel.java#L325) in a HashMap, the Sink is terminated

1. If service request scheduling fails,
1. When receiving the corresponding service response,
2. Or at the time of closing the RRChannel object.

Clearly, none of the above routes terminated the Sink, resulting in downstream `authorize()` waiting forever.

### Digging further down in the subgraph (part 2)

With the above understanding, flow results in the three partition receivers (1, 2, and 3) hanging is proven to be below. 

1. From `authorize()`, the RRChannel::sendWithAck is called when the RRChannel was not disposed. It enqueued a [work](https://github.com/Azure/azure-sdk-for-java/blob/a7060c45b016da37399106e1adb7f8f2e8a2991d/sdk/core/azure-core-amqp/src/main/java/com/azure/core/amqp/implementation/RequestResponseChannel.java#L328) (not executed yet) to the ProtonJ message pump thread. The temporary logging we added confirms this call by printing RRChannel's dispose state and ObjectId. 
> 2022-03-05 09:13:02.536 [reactor-executor-1] [INFO] c.a.c.a.i.RequestResponseChannel - {"az.sdk.message":"RRChannel::sendWithAck linkName:1_6c9bc5_1646500372433 isDisposed:false ObjectId
:9fc336","connectionId":"MF_f39d21_1646500370415","linkName":"cbs"}
2. Service traffic results in RRChannel's Send and Receive Links closure, marking RRChannel as disposed. The temporary logging we added confirms this.
> 2022-03-05 09:13:02.623 [reactor-executor-1] [DEBUG] c.a.c.a.i.RequestResponseChannel - {"az.sdk.message":"Closing request/response channel. ObjectId :9fc336","connectionId":"MF_f39d21_1646500370415","linkName":"cbs"}
3. The connection is not closed yet or closed, but the propagation of the closure event is in progress, and the ProtonJ message pump is healthy; hence it executes the work enqueued by 1. The temporary logging we added shows the RRChannel is already disposed of by this time.
> 2022-03-05 09:13:02.636 [reactor-executor-1] [INFO] c.a.c.a.i.RequestResponseChannel - {"az.sdk.message":"RRChannel::sendWithAck -> Dispatcher.invoke linkName:1_6c9bc5_1646500372433 isDisposed:true ObjectId :9fc336","connectionId":"MF_f39d21_1646500370415","linkName":"cbs"}
4. The work attempted to [use](https://github.com/Azure/azure-sdk-for-java/blob/400f6198aaf1258ec0b57a2bebc59ff9e7ac81ae/sdk/core/azure-core-amqp/src/main/java/com/azure/core/amqp/implementation/RequestResponseChannel.java#L345) the disposed ProtonJ Sender object, throwing IllegalStateException; this exception is caught and [logged](https://github.com/Azure/azure-sdk-for-java/blob/400f6198aaf1258ec0b57a2bebc59ff9e7ac81ae/sdk/core/azure-core-amqp/src/main/java/com/azure/core/amqp/implementation/ReactorExecutor.java#L110) by the "global handler" of message pump.
> o.a.q.p.e.HandlerException: java.lang.IllegalStateException: send not allowed after the sender is closed.
	at o.a.q.p.e.impl.EventImpl.dispatch(EventImpl.java:112) ...
5. The above-outlined flow results in the Sink(s) being never terminated, causing `authorize` to wait forever, which inturn results in partition 1, 2 and 3 to never recover.

## The code fix

Now we know the exact reason, the fix is as simple as checking dispose state at the time of "execution".

```java
if (isDisposed() 
    || sendLink.getLocalState() == EndpointState.CLOSED 
    || receiveLink.getLocalState() == EndpointState.CLOSED) {
    sink.error(new IllegalStateException("Cannot send a message when request response channel is disposed."));
    return;
}
```

Emitting IllegalStateException like this during "execution" aligns with the similar error emission from [here](https://github.com/Azure/azure-sdk-for-java/blob/400f6198aaf1258ec0b57a2bebc59ff9e7ac81ae/sdk/core/azure-core-amqp/src/main/java/com/azure/core/amqp/implementation/RequestResponseChannel.java#L298) at the time of "scheduling". 

Note that this fix will not result in the faulted low-level receiver resuming. Instead, once the fix is in, the application using a "low-level receiver" will get notified about the error, upon which the application can recreate the receiver. 

For the application using "processor receiver", it currently hangs. But once the fix is in, the processor internally handles the error from it's "low-level receiver" and recovers for the user.

## Thoughts:

Look at other places in the SDK that can be affected in the same fashion.

The service bus user running into this specific race case: https://github.com/Azure/azure-sdk-for-java/issues/23398

'https://api.github.com/users/lmolkova/events{/privacy}', 'received_events_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/lmolkova/received_events', 'type': 'User', 'site_admin': False}, 'body': 'Fixes #26676

When log level is **not** configured and `DefaultLogger` is used (there is no SLF4J logger implementation on the classpath) `DefaultLogger` constructor sets log level in constructor which causes env var lookup.
Since env var is not set up, the result is not cached and each constructor call causes lookup. 

It should be fine in most cases, but not when loggers are created on the hot path (e.g. ServiceBus creates loggers in [SynchronousReceiveWork](https://github.com/Azure/azure-sdk-for-java/blob/main/sdk/servicebus/azure-messaging-servicebus/src/main/java/com/azure/messaging/servicebus/SynchronousReceiveWork.java) and there other cases like this). It might not be reasonable to always use a static logger (e.g. when adding per-logger instance context).

Since changing env variables at runtime is not really supported, there is no benefit in re-reading property every time new logger is created and it can be done statically.

This PR aims to reduce the number of instances the SDKs buffer memory or optimize the cases where buffering is required.

**Current Changes**

- New method `writeByteBufferToStream` added to `CoreUtils`. Contains optimizations on accessing or writing the contents of the `ByteBuffer` into an `OutputStream`.
- `FluxUtil.toFluxByteBuffer` added an optimization when the `InputStream` is a `FileInputStream`. The `FileChannel` backing the `FileInputStream` is used to get `MappedByteBuffer`s which defers loading the file's contents into memory until it's used.

'body': "# Description This PR aims to reduce the number of instances the SDKs buffer memory or optimize the cases where buffering is required. **Current Changes** - New method `writeByteBufferToStream` added to `CoreUtils`. Contains optimizations on accessing or writing the contents of the `ByteBuffer` into an `OutputStream`. - `FluxUtil.toFluxByteBuffer` added an optimization when the `InputStream` is a `FileInputStream`. The `FileChannel` backing the `FileInputStream` is used to get `MappedByteBuffer`s which defers loading the file's contents into memory until it's used. # All SDK Contribution checklist: - [x] **The pull request does not introduce [breaking changes]** - [x] **CHANGELOG is updated for new features, bug fixes or other significant changes.** - [x] **I have read the [contribution guidelines](https://github.com/Azure/azure-sdk-for-java/blob/main/CONTRIBUTING.md).** ## [General Guidelines and Best Practices](https://github.com/Azure/azure-sdk-for-java/blob/main/CONTRIBUTING.md#developer-guide) - [x] Title of the pull request is clear and informative. - [x] There are a small number of commits, each of which have an informative message. 'received_events_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/alzimmermsft/received_events', 'type': 'User', 'site_admin': False}, 'body': "# Description

This PR aims to reduce the number of instances the SDKs buffer memory or optimize the cases where buffering is required.

**Current Changes**

- New method `writeByteBufferToStream` added to `CoreUtils`. Contains optimizations on accessing or writing the contents of the `ByteBuffer` into an `OutputStream`.
- `FluxUtil.toFluxByteBuffer` added an optimization when the `InputStream` is a `FileInputStream`. The `FileChannel` backing the `FileInputStream` is used to get `MappedByteBuffer`s which defers loading the file's contents into memory until it's used.

# All SDK Contribution checklist:

'received_events_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/alzimmermsft/received_events', 'type': 'User', 'site_admin': False}, 'body': "# Description

This PR aims to reduce the number of instances the SDKs buffer memory or optimize the cases where buffering is required.

**Current Changes**

- New method `writeByteBufferToStream` added to `CoreUtils`. Contains optimizations on accessing or writing the contents of the `ByteBuffer` into an `OutputStream`.
- `FluxUtil.toFluxByteBuffer` added an optimization when the `InputStream` is a `FileInputStream`. The `FileChannel` backing the `FileInputStream` is used to get `MappedByteBuffer`s which defers loading the file's contents into memory until it's used.

# All SDK Contribution checklist:

'https://api.github.com/users/vcolin7/received_events', 'type': 'User', 'site_admin': False}, 'body': "Fixes: #24951. Here's the [APIView link](https://apiview.dev/Assemblies/Review/c8986bdf9191490b875c0a925246193d?diffRevisionId=ec4d9dfda8184e3a9f519e5dc459d73b&doc=False&diffOnly=False#com.azure.security.keyvault.keys.models.KeyReleasePolicy) with the feedback. Applied the following changes: - Removed an exports statement for `com.azure.security.keyvault.keys.implementation` in `module-info.java`. [1](https://apiview.dev/Assemblies/Review/c8986bdf9191490b875c0a925246193d?diffRevisionId=ec4d9dfda8184e3a9f519e5dc459d73b&doc=False&diffOnly=False#6f9403846d824dbbaf25fecab330764b) - Added the `@ServiceMethod` annotation to `KeyClient`'s `getRandomBytes()` and `getRandomBytesWithResponse()`. [2](https://apiview.dev/Assemblies/Review/c8986bdf9191490b875c0a925246193d?diffRevisionId=ec4d9dfda8184e3a9f519e5dc459d73b&doc=False&diffOnly=False#dcbc86f5545c48a5ac4f9b8688773a25) - `KeyReleasePolicy` - Renamed `data` to `encodedPolicy`[3](https://github.com/Azure/azure-sdk-for-net/issues/24876) and changed its type from `byte[]` to `BinaryData`.[4](https://apiview.dev/Assemblies/Review/c8986bdf9191490b875c0a925246193d?diffRevisionId=ec4d9dfda8184e3a9f519e5dc459d73b&doc=False&diffOnly=False#1d3836a11b2f4670b52c294cdb41e9e9) - Flattened `KeyRotationPolicyProperties` into `KeyRotationPolicy`.[5](https://apiview.dev/Assemblies/Review/c8986bdf9191490b875c0a925246193d?diffRevisionId=ec4d9dfda8184e3a9f519e5dc459d73b&doc=False&diffOnly=False#4328658981154199bff7aef0fd0adf8e)[6](https://apiview.dev/Assemblies/Review/c8986bdf9191490b875c0a925246193d?diffRevisionId=ec4d9dfda8184e3a9f519e5dc459d73b&doc=False&diffOnly=False#597b07320dfa4735adb7b4d7ac8941bd)[7](https://apiview.dev/Assemblies/Review/c8986bdf9191490b875c0a925246193d?diffRevisionId=ec4d9dfda8184e3a9f519e5dc459d73b&doc=False&diffOnly=False#597b07320dfa4735adb7b4d7ac8941bd) - Renamed `expiryTime` to `expiresIn`.[8](https://apiview.dev/Assemblies/Review/c8986bdf9191490b875c0a925246193d?diffRevisionId=ec4d9dfda8184e3a9f519e5dc459d73b&doc=False&diffOnly=False#a08c547b756d4cf29204db6e852eea78) - Added the `immutable` property, as it will be included the next service version to be released. - Renamed `target` to `targetAttestationToken` in `releaseKey` Here's the [APIView link](https://apiview.dev/Assemblies/Review/c8986bdf9191490b875c0a925246193d?diffRevisionId=ec4d9dfda8184e3a9f519e5dc459d73b&doc=False&diffOnly=False#com.azure.security.keyvault.keys.models.KeyReleasePolicy) with the feedback.

Applied the following changes:

- Removed an exports statement for `com.azure.security.keyvault.keys.implementation` in `module-info.java`. <sup>[1](https://apiview.dev/Assemblies/Review/c8986bdf9191490b875c0a925246193d?diffRevisionId=ec4d9dfda8184e3a9f519e5dc459d73b&doc=False&diffOnly=False#6f9403846d824dbbaf25fecab330764b)</sup>
- Added the `@ServiceMethod` annotation to `KeyClient`'s `getRandomBytes()` and `getRandomBytesWithResponse()`. <sup>[2](https://apiview.dev/Assemblies/Review/c8986bdf9191490b875c0a925246193d?diffRevisionId=ec4d9dfda8184e3a9f519e5dc459d73b&doc=False&diffOnly=False#dcbc86f5545c48a5ac4f9b8688773a25)</sup>
- `KeyReleasePolicy`
    - Renamed `data` to `encodedPolicy`<sup>[3](https://github.com/Azure/azure-sdk-for-net/issues/24876)</sup> and changed its type from `byte[]` to `BinaryData`.<sup>[4](https://apiview.dev/Assemblies/Review/c8986bdf9191490b875c0a925246193d?diffRevisionId=ec4d9dfda8184e3a9f519e5dc459d73b&doc=False&diffOnly=False#1d3836a11b2f4670b52c294cdb41e9e9)</sup>
    - Flattened `KeyRotationPolicyProperties` into `KeyRotationPolicy`.<sup>[5](https://apiview.dev/Assemblies/Review/c8986bdf9191490b875c0a925246193d?diffRevisionId=ec4d9dfda8184e3a9f519e5dc459d73b&doc=False&diffOnly=False#4328658981154199bff7aef0fd0adf8e)[6](https://apiview.dev/Assemblies/Review/c8986bdf9191490b875c0a925246193d?diffRevisionId=ec4d9dfda8184e3a9f519e5dc459d73b&doc=False&diffOnly=False#597b07320dfa4735adb7b4d7ac8941bd)[7](https://apiview.dev/Assemblies/Review/c8986bdf9191490b875c0a925246193d?diffRevisionId=ec4d9dfda8184e3a9f519e5dc459d73b&doc=False&diffOnly=False#597b07320dfa4735adb7b4d7ac8941bd)</sup>
    - Renamed `expiryTime` to `expiresIn`.<sup>[8](https://apiview.dev/Assemblies/Review/c8986bdf9191490b875c0a925246193d?diffRevisionId=ec4d9dfda8184e3a9f519e5dc459d73b&doc=False&diffOnly=False#a08c547b756d4cf29204db6e852eea78)</sup>
    - Added the `immutable` property, as it will be included the next service version to be released.
- Renamed `target` to `targetAttestationToken` in `releaseKey` APIs.<sup>[9](https://github.com/Azure/azure-sdk-for-net/issues/24876)</sup>
- Removed `KeyExportRequestParameters` as the `/export` operation will be pushed to a future service version.
- Renamed `KeyRotationLifetimeAction`'s `type` to `action`, to align with existing similar APIs in Key Vault Certificates.<sup>[10](https://apiview.dev/Assemblies/Review/d2d05cf175c7478184662d580a300e68?diffRevisionId=e229c861eb9940de96b6adc1d5a8e5b1&doc=False&diffOnly=False#821277d446d24f7192a329e5f9b99c34)</sup>", #24951.

Here's the [APIView link](https://apiview.dev/Assemblies/Review/c8986bdf9191490b875c0a925246193d?diffRevisionId=ec4d9dfda8184e3a9f519e5dc459d73b&doc=False&diffOnly=False#com.azure.security.keyvault.keys.models.KeyReleasePolicy) with the feedback.

Applied the following changes:

- Removed an exports statement for `com.azure.security.keyvault.keys.implementation` in `module-info.java`. <sup>[1](https://apiview.dev/Assemblies/Review/c8986bdf9191490b875c0a925246193d?diffRevisionId=ec4d9dfda8184e3a9f519e5dc459d73b&doc=False&diffOnly=False#6f9403846d824dbbaf25fecab330764b)</sup>
- Added the `@ServiceMethod` annotation to `KeyClient`'s `getRandomBytes()` and `getRandomBytesWithResponse()`. <sup>[2](https://apiview.dev/Assemblies/Review/c8986bdf9191490b875c0a925246193d?diffRevisionId=ec4d9dfda8184e3a9f519e5dc459d73b&doc=False&diffOnly=False#dcbc86f5545c48a5ac4f9b8688773a25)</sup>
- `KeyReleasePolicy`
    - Renamed `data` to `encodedPolicy`<sup>[3](https://github.com/Azure/azure-sdk-for-net/issues/24876)</sup> and changed its type from `byte[]` to `BinaryData`.<sup>[4](https://apiview.dev/Assemblies/Review/c8986bdf9191490b875c0a925246193d?diffRevisionId=ec4d9dfda8184e3a9f519e5dc459d73b&doc=False&diffOnly=False#1d3836a11b2f4670b52c294cdb41e9e9)</sup>
    - Flattened `KeyRotationPolicyProperties` into `KeyRotationPolicy`.<sup>[5](https://apiview.dev/Assemblies/Review/c8986bdf9191490b875c0a925246193d?diffRevisionId=ec4d9dfda8184e3a9f519e5dc459d73b&doc=False&diffOnly=False#4328658981154199bff7aef0fd0adf8e)[6](https://apiview.dev/Assemblies/Review/c8986bdf9191490b875c0a925246193d?diffRevisionId=ec4d9dfda8184e3a9f519e5dc459d73b&doc=False&diffOnly=False#597b07320dfa4735adb7b4d7ac8941bd)[7](https://apiview.dev/Assemblies/Review/c8986bdf9191490b875c0a925246193d?diffRevisionId=ec4d9dfda8184e3a9f519e5dc459d73b&doc=False&diffOnly=False#597b07320dfa4735adb7b4d7ac8941bd)</sup>
    - Renamed `expiryTime` to `expiresIn`.<sup>[8](https://apiview.dev/Assemblies/Review/c8986bdf9191490b875c0a925246193d?diffRevisionId=ec4d9dfda8184e3a9f519e5dc459d73b&doc=False&diffOnly=False#a08c547b756d4cf29204db6e852eea78)</sup>
    - Added the `immutable` property, as it will be included the next service version to be released.
- Renamed `target` to `targetAttestationToken` in `releaseKey` APIs.<sup>[9](https://github.com/Azure/azure-sdk-for-net/issues/24876)</sup>
- Removed `KeyExportRequestParameters` as the `/export` operation will be pushed to a future service version.
- Renamed `KeyRotationLifetimeAction`'s `type` to `action`, to align with existing similar APIs in Key Vault Certificates.<sup>[10](https://apiview.dev/Assemblies/Review/d2d05cf175c7478184662d580a300e68?diffRevisionId=e229c861eb9940de96b6adc1d5a8e5b1&doc=False&diffOnly=False#821277d446d24f7192a329e5f9b99c34)</sup>", Here's the [APIView link](https://apiview.dev/Assemblies/Review/c8986bdf9191490b875c0a925246193d?diffRevisionId=ec4d9dfda8184e3a9f519e5dc459d73b&doc=False&diffOnly=False#com.azure.security.keyvault.keys.models.KeyReleasePolicy) with the feedback.

Applied the following changes:

- Removed an exports statement for `com.azure.security.keyvault.keys.implementation` in `module-info.java`. <sup>[1](https://apiview.dev/Assemblies/Review/c8986bdf9191490b875c0a925246193d?diffRevisionId=ec4d9dfda8184e3a9f519e5dc459d73b&doc=False&diffOnly=False#6f9403846d824dbbaf25fecab330764b)</sup>
- Added the `@ServiceMethod` annotation to `KeyClient`'s `getRandomBytes()` and `getRandomBytesWithResponse()`. <sup>[2](https://apiview.dev/Assemblies/Review/c8986bdf9191490b875c0a925246193d?diffRevisionId=ec4d9dfda8184e3a9f519e5dc459d73b&doc=False&diffOnly=False#dcbc86f5545c48a5ac4f9b8688773a25)</sup>
- `KeyReleasePolicy`
    - Renamed `data` to `encodedPolicy`<sup>[3](https://github.com/Azure/azure-sdk-for-net/issues/24876)</sup> and changed its type from `byte[]` to `BinaryData`.<sup>[4](https://apiview.dev/Assemblies/Review/c8986bdf9191490b875c0a925246193d?diffRevisionId=ec4d9dfda8184e3a9f519e5dc459d73b&doc=False&diffOnly=False#1d3836a11b2f4670b52c294cdb41e9e9)</sup>
    - Flattened `KeyRotationPolicyProperties` into `KeyRotationPolicy`.<sup>[5](https://apiview.dev/Assemblies/Review/c8986bdf9191490b875c0a925246193d?diffRevisionId=ec4d9dfda8184e3a9f519e5dc459d73b&doc=False&diffOnly=False#4328658981154199bff7aef0fd0adf8e)[6](https://apiview.dev/Assemblies/Review/c8986bdf9191490b875c0a925246193d?diffRevisionId=ec4d9dfda8184e3a9f519e5dc459d73b&doc=False&diffOnly=False#597b07320dfa4735adb7b4d7ac8941bd)[7](https://apiview.dev/Assemblies/Review/c8986bdf9191490b875c0a925246193d?diffRevisionId=ec4d9dfda8184e3a9f519e5dc459d73b&doc=False&diffOnly=False#597b07320dfa4735adb7b4d7ac8941bd)</sup>
    - Renamed `expiryTime` to `expiresIn`.<sup>[8](https://apiview.dev/Assemblies/Review/c8986bdf9191490b875c0a925246193d?diffRevisionId=ec4d9dfda8184e3a9f519e5dc459d73b&doc=False&diffOnly=False#a08c547b756d4cf29204db6e852eea78)</sup>
    - Added the `immutable` property, as it will be included the next service version to be released.
- Renamed `target` to `targetAttestationToken` in `releaseKey` APIs.<sup>[9](https://github.com/Azure/azure-sdk-for-net/issues/24876)</sup>
- Removed `KeyExportRequestParameters` as the `/export` operation will be pushed to a future service version.
- Renamed `KeyRotationLifetimeAction`'s `type` to `action`, to align with existing similar APIs in Key Vault Certificates.<sup>[10](https://apiview.dev/Assemblies/Review/d2d05cf175c7478184662d580a300e68?diffRevisionId=e229c861eb9940de96b6adc1d5a8e5b1&doc=False&diffOnly=False#821277d446d24f7192a329e5f9b99c34)</sup>", Here's the [APIView link](https://apiview.dev/Assemblies/Review/c8986bdf9191490b875c0a925246193d?diffRevisionId=ec4d9dfda8184e3a9f519e5dc459d73b&doc=False&diffOnly=False#com.azure.security.keyvault.keys.models.KeyReleasePolicy) with the feedback.

Applied the following changes:

- Removed an exports statement for `com.azure.security.keyvault.keys.implementation` in `module-info.java`. <sup>[1](https://apiview.dev/Assemblies/Review/c8986bdf9191490b875c0a925246193d?diffRevisionId=ec4d9dfda8184e3a9f519e5dc459d73b&doc=False&diffOnly=False#6f9403846d824dbbaf25fecab330764b)</sup>
- Added the `@ServiceMethod` annotation to `KeyClient`'s `getRandomBytes()` and `getRandomBytesWithResponse()`. <sup>[2](https://apiview.dev/Assemblies/Review/c8986bdf9191490b875c0a925246193d?diffRevisionId=ec4d9dfda8184e3a9f519e5dc459d73b&doc=False&diffOnly=False#dcbc86f5545c48a5ac4f9b8688773a25)</sup>
- `KeyReleasePolicy`
    - Renamed `data` to `encodedPolicy`<sup>[3](https://github.com/Azure/azure-sdk-for-net/issues/24876)</sup> and changed its type from `byte[]` to `BinaryData`.<sup>[4](https://apiview.dev/Assemblies/Review/c8986bdf9191490b875c0a925246193d?diffRevisionId=ec4d9dfda8184e3a9f519e5dc459d73b&doc=False&diffOnly=False#1d3836a11b2f4670b52c294cdb41e9e9)</sup>
    - Flattened `KeyRotationPolicyProperties` into `KeyRotationPolicy`.<sup>[5](https://apiview.dev/Assemblies/Review/c8986bdf9191490b875c0a925246193d?diffRevisionId=ec4d9dfda8184e3a9f519e5dc459d73b&doc=False&diffOnly=False#4328658981154199bff7aef0fd0adf8e)[6](https://apiview.dev/Assemblies/Review/c8986bdf9191490b875c0a925246193d?diffRevisionId=ec4d9dfda8184e3a9f519e5dc459d73b&doc=False&diffOnly=False#597b07320dfa4735adb7b4d7ac8941bd)[7](https://apiview.dev/Assemblies/Review/c8986bdf9191490b875c0a925246193d?diffRevisionId=ec4d9dfda8184e3a9f519e5dc459d73b&doc=False&diffOnly=False#597b07320dfa4735adb7b4d7ac8941bd)</sup>
    - Renamed `expiryTime` to `expiresIn`.<sup>[8](https://apiview.dev/Assemblies/Review/c8986bdf9191490b875c0a925246193d?diffRevisionId=ec4d9dfda8184e3a9f519e5dc459d73b&doc=False&diffOnly=False#a08c547b756d4cf29204db6e852eea78)</sup>
    - Added the `immutable` property, as it will be included the next service version to be released.
- Renamed `target` to `targetAttestationToken` in `releaseKey` APIs.<sup>[9](https://github.com/Azure/azure-sdk-for-net/issues/24876)</sup>
- Removed `KeyExportRequestParameters` as the `/export` operation will be pushed to a future service version.
- Renamed `KeyRotationLifetimeAction`'s `type` to `action`, to align with existing similar APIs in Key Vault Certificates.<sup>[10](https://apiview.dev/Assemblies/Review/d2d05cf175c7478184662d580a300e68?diffRevisionId=e229c861eb9940de96b6adc1d5a8e5b1&doc=False&diffOnly=False#821277d446d24f7192a329e5f9b99c34)</sup>", - Removed an exports statement for `com.azure.security.keyvault.keys.implementation` in `module-info.java`. <sup>[1](https://apiview.dev/Assemblies/Review/c8986bdf9191490b875c0a925246193d?diffRevisionId=ec4d9dfda8184e3a9f519e5dc459d73b&doc=False&diffOnly=False#6f9403846d824dbbaf25fecab330764b)</sup>
- Added the `@ServiceMethod` annotation to `KeyClient`'s `getRandomBytes()` and `getRandomBytesWithResponse()`. <sup>[2](https://apiview.dev/Assemblies/Review/c8986bdf9191490b875c0a925246193d?diffRevisionId=ec4d9dfda8184e3a9f519e5dc459d73b&doc=False&diffOnly=False#dcbc86f5545c48a5ac4f9b8688773a25)</sup>
- `KeyReleasePolicy`
    - Renamed `data` to `encodedPolicy`<sup>[3](https://github.com/Azure/azure-sdk-for-net/issues/24876)</sup> and changed its type from `byte[]` to `BinaryData`.<sup>[4](https://apiview.dev/Assemblies/Review/c8986bdf9191490b875c0a925246193d?diffRevisionId=ec4d9dfda8184e3a9f519e5dc459d73b&doc=False&diffOnly=False#1d3836a11b2f4670b52c294cdb41e9e9)</sup>
    - Flattened `KeyRotationPolicyProperties` into `KeyRotationPolicy`.<sup>[5](https://apiview.dev/Assemblies/Review/c8986bdf9191490b875c0a925246193d?diffRevisionId=ec4d9dfda8184e3a9f519e5dc459d73b&doc=False&diffOnly=False#4328658981154199bff7aef0fd0adf8e)[6](https://apiview.dev/Assemblies/Review/c8986bdf9191490b875c0a925246193d?diffRevisionId=ec4d9dfda8184e3a9f519e5dc459d73b&doc=False&diffOnly=False#597b07320dfa4735adb7b4d7ac8941bd)[7](https://apiview.dev/Assemblies/Review/c8986bdf9191490b875c0a925246193d?diffRevisionId=ec4d9dfda8184e3a9f519e5dc459d73b&doc=False&diffOnly=False#597b07320dfa4735adb7b4d7ac8941bd)</sup>
    - Renamed `expiryTime` to `expiresIn`.<sup>[8](https://apiview.dev/Assemblies/Review/c8986bdf9191490b875c0a925246193d?diffRevisionId=ec4d9dfda8184e3a9f519e5dc459d73b&doc=False&diffOnly=False#a08c547b756d4cf29204db6e852eea78)</sup>
    - Added the `immutable` property, as it will be included the next service version to be released.
- Renamed `target` to `targetAttestationToken` in `releaseKey` APIs.<sup>[9](https://github.com/Azure/azure-sdk-for-net/issues/24876)</sup>
- Removed `KeyExportRequestParameters` as the `/export` operation will be pushed to a future service version.
- Renamed `KeyRotationLifetimeAction`'s `type` to `action`, to align with existing similar APIs in Key Vault Certificates.<sup>[10](https://apiview.dev/Assemblies/Review/d2d05cf175c7478184662d580a300e68?diffRevisionId=e229c861eb9940de96b6adc1d5a8e5b1&doc=False&diffOnly=False#821277d446d24f7192a329e5f9b99c34)</sup>", Here's the [APIView link](https://apiview.dev/Assemblies/Review/c8986bdf9191490b875c0a925246193d?diffRevisionId=ec4d9dfda8184e3a9f519e5dc459d73b&doc=False&diffOnly=False#com.azure.security.keyvault.keys.models.KeyReleasePolicy) with the feedback.

Applied the following changes:

- Removed an exports statement for `com.azure.security.keyvault.keys.implementation` in `module-info.java`. <sup>[1](https://apiview.dev/Assemblies/Review/c8986bdf9191490b875c0a925246193d?diffRevisionId=ec4d9dfda8184e3a9f519e5dc459d73b&doc=False&diffOnly=False#6f9403846d824dbbaf25fecab330764b)</sup>
- Added the `@ServiceMethod` annotation to `KeyClient`'s `getRandomBytes()` and `getRandomBytesWithResponse()`. <sup>[2](https://apiview.dev/Assemblies/Review/c8986bdf9191490b875c0a925246193d?diffRevisionId=ec4d9dfda8184e3a9f519e5dc459d73b&doc=False&diffOnly=False#dcbc86f5545c48a5ac4f9b8688773a25)</sup>
- `KeyReleasePolicy`
    - Renamed `data` to `encodedPolicy`<sup>[3](https://github.com/Azure/azure-sdk-for-net/issues/24876)</sup> and changed its type from `byte[]` to `BinaryData`.<sup>[4](https://apiview.dev/Assemblies/Review/c8986bdf9191490b875c0a925246193d?diffRevisionId=ec4d9dfda8184e3a9f519e5dc459d73b&doc=False&diffOnly=False#1d3836a11b2f4670b52c294cdb41e9e9)</sup>
    - Flattened `KeyRotationPolicyProperties` into `KeyRotationPolicy`.<sup>[5](https://apiview.dev/Assemblies/Review/c8986bdf9191490b875c0a925246193d?diffRevisionId=ec4d9dfda8184e3a9f519e5dc459d73b&doc=False&diffOnly=False#4328658981154199bff7aef0fd0adf8e)[6](https://apiview.dev/Assemblies/Review/c8986bdf9191490b875c0a925246193d?diffRevisionId=ec4d9dfda8184e3a9f519e5dc459d73b&doc=False&diffOnly=False#597b07320dfa4735adb7b4d7ac8941bd)[7](https://apiview.dev/Assemblies/Review/c8986bdf9191490b875c0a925246193d?diffRevisionId=ec4d9dfda8184e3a9f519e5dc459d73b&doc=False&diffOnly=False#597b07320dfa4735adb7b4d7ac8941bd)</sup>
    - Renamed `expiryTime` to `expiresIn`.<sup>[8](https://apiview.dev/Assemblies/Review/c8986bdf9191490b875c0a925246193d?diffRevisionId=ec4d9dfda8184e3a9f519e5dc459d73b&doc=False&diffOnly=False#a08c547b756d4cf29204db6e852eea78)</sup>
    - Added the `immutable` property, as it will be included the next service version to be released.
- Renamed `target` to `targetAttestationToken` in `releaseKey` APIs.<sup>[9](https://github.com/Azure/azure-sdk-for-net/issues/24876)</sup>
- Removed `KeyExportRequestParameters` as the `/export` operation will be pushed to a future service version.
- Renamed `KeyRotationLifetimeAction`'s `type` to `action`, to align with existing similar APIs in Key Vault Certificates.<sup>[10](https://apiview.dev/Assemblies/Review/d2d05cf175c7478184662d580a300e68?diffRevisionId=e229c861eb9940de96b6adc1d5a8e5b1&doc=False&diffOnly=False#821277d446d24f7192a329e5f9b99c34)</sup>", Here's the [APIView link](https://apiview.dev/Assemblies/Review/c8986bdf9191490b875c0a925246193d?diffRevisionId=ec4d9dfda8184e3a9f519e5dc459d73b&doc=False&diffOnly=False#com.azure.security.keyvault.keys.models.KeyReleasePolicy) with the feedback.

Applied the following changes:

- Removed an exports statement for `com.azure.security.keyvault.keys.implementation` in `module-info.java`. <sup>[1](https://apiview.dev/Assemblies/Review/c8986bdf9191490b875c0a925246193d?diffRevisionId=ec4d9dfda8184e3a9f519e5dc459d73b&doc=False&diffOnly=False#6f9403846d824dbbaf25fecab330764b)</sup>
- Added the `@ServiceMethod` annotation to `KeyClient`'s `getRandomBytes()` and `getRandomBytesWithResponse()`. <sup>[2](https://apiview.dev/Assemblies/Review/c8986bdf9191490b875c0a925246193d?diffRevisionId=ec4d9dfda8184e3a9f519e5dc459d73b&doc=False&diffOnly=False#dcbc86f5545c48a5ac4f9b8688773a25)</sup>
- `KeyReleasePolicy`
    - Renamed `data` to `encodedPolicy`<sup>[3](https://github.com/Azure/azure-sdk-for-net/issues/24876)</sup> and changed its type from `byte[]` to `BinaryData`.<sup>[4](https://apiview.dev/Assemblies/Review/c8986bdf9191490b875c0a925246193d?diffRevisionId=ec4d9dfda8184e3a9f519e5dc459d73b&doc=False&diffOnly=False#1d3836a11b2f4670b52c294cdb41e9e9)</sup>
    - Flattened `KeyRotationPolicyProperties` into `KeyRotationPolicy`.<sup>[5](https://apiview.dev/Assemblies/Review/c8986bdf9191490b875c0a925246193d?diffRevisionId=ec4d9dfda8184e3a9f519e5dc459d73b&doc=False&diffOnly=False#4328658981154199bff7aef0fd0adf8e)[6](https://apiview.dev/Assemblies/Review/c8986bdf9191490b875c0a925246193d?diffRevisionId=ec4d9dfda8184e3a9f519e5dc459d73b&doc=False&diffOnly=False#597b07320dfa4735adb7b4d7ac8941bd)[7](https://apiview.dev/Assemblies/Review/c8986bdf9191490b875c0a925246193d?diffRevisionId=ec4d9dfda8184e3a9f519e5dc459d73b&doc=False&diffOnly=False#597b07320dfa4735adb7b4d7ac8941bd)</sup>
    - Renamed `expiryTime` to `expiresIn`.<sup>[8](https://apiview.dev/Assemblies/Review/c8986bdf9191490b875c0a925246193d?diffRevisionId=ec4d9dfda8184e3a9f519e5dc459d73b&doc=False&diffOnly=False#a08c547b756d4cf29204db6e852eea78)</sup>
    - Added the `immutable` property, as it will be included the next service version to be released.
- Renamed `target` to `targetAttestationToken` in `releaseKey` APIs.<sup>[9](https://github.com/Azure/azure-sdk-for-net/issues/24876)</sup>
- Removed `KeyExportRequestParameters` as the `/export` operation will be pushed to a future service version.
- Renamed `KeyRotationLifetimeAction`'s `type` to `action`, to align with existing similar APIs in Key Vault Certificates.<sup>[10](https://apiview.dev/Assemblies/Review/d2d05cf175c7478184662d580a300e68?diffRevisionId=e229c861eb9940de96b6adc1d5a8e5b1&doc=False&diffOnly=False#821277d446d24f7192a329e5f9b99c34)</sup>", 'updated_at': '2022-01-31T16:52:16Z', 'closed_at': '2022-01-31T16:38:03Z', 'author_association': 'MEMBER', 'active_lock_reason': None, 'body': '### Update: this has been postponed, see announcement [below](https://github.com/reactor/reactor/issues/705#issuecomment-1025976281)

------

This issue exposes the general rationale for a Generation 4 of Reactor.

Below are other issues around that topic, which focus on more specific aspects:
 - [#704] Reactor 3 must be able to run alongside Reactor 4
 - [#703] JDK 17 baseline
 - ...

## Preamble: What of Reactor 3

We want to start by making one thing clear: Reactor 3 isn't going away.

The current plan is that the `Europium` line (aka BOM `2020.0.x`, aka reactor-core `3.4.x`) is going to be turned into an LTS,
with support extended for at least a couple of years past the GA release of Reactor 4.

We thought about a 3.5.x LTS, but compared to turning Europium into LTS it doesn't bring much to the table.

Actually, since there would be no Spring release to consume it, it would be invisible to a majority of our user base.
(yes, we have users that directly depend on Reactor rather than through Spring, but given the pervasiveness of the framework,
we can expect that in the end not a lot of applications using Reactor are completely Spring-free...

With an LTS, we give users that cannot upgrade to the next generation a way out.

But it becomes important that Reactor 3 can run alongside Reactor 4 for that to be a practical option.

Issue https://github.com/reactor/reactor/issues/704 is focusing on that aspect.

## Internal "protocol" rework

When a `Reactor` `Subscriber` connects with a `Reactor` `Publisher`, they recognize that they are part of the same library
and as such can relax a bit wrt Reactive Streams protocol, by making some assumptions about how the other party is implemented.

It also enables some sort of Reactor-specific RS protocol.
For instance, operator fusion becomes possible (which improves performance), `Context` is made accessible to the `Subscription`s,
etc...

With some R&D, these internal protocols could be improved in order to better integrate modern concerns like:
 - `Context` propagation
 - observability (tracing, logging, metrics)
 - lifecycle management and avoiding leaks (`doOnDiscard`)
 - ...

In the current state, we feel we've come to the limit of what can be done in Reactor 3.
By giving ourselves the opportunity to break the current internals, there's more room for innovative solutions to these problems.


## Changes to the original tradeoffs

When Reactor 3 was designed, a number of trade offs were made.
Notably, one around balancing performance vs user-driven backpressure.

After 5 years, we now think different tradeoffs now make more sense.

Since these can lead to subverted expectations around "the default behavior"
of a `Flux` or `Mono`, there is absolutely no way they can be introduced in
a Reactor 3 release.

Ideas include:

 - reduce the amount of implicit backpressure (aka prefetch)
 - make `Mono` even lazier (by triggering behavior on first request rather than subscription)

## Netty 5

Reactor is applicable to many domains, but network I/O is a huge one among these.
No wonder `Reactor-Netty` is only second to `Reactor-Core` in the portfolio of projects.

`Netty 5` is the next generation of non-blocking network I/O libraries.
But `Reactor-Netty` exposes a lot of `Netty` concepts and classes, translating the rest into reactive APIs.
As such, `Reactor-Netty` `1.x` cannot really switch to Netty 5 without breakage.

This implies a `Reactor-Netty` 2.x generation.

Since Netty 5 will be baselined on **Java 11**, this also implies a similar baseline change in `Reactor-Netty`
(which could only happen in a new generation anyway).


## Spring 6

Last but not least, a majority of our user base either directly comes from Spring or uses Reactor in the context of a Spring-based application.

Even though Reactor doesn't depend on the Spring ecosystem, Spring Framework/Boot/Data/Gateway/... have all immensely contributed to the success of the library.
They are important stakeholders, and if there isn't a Spring release that is going to use our stuff, then it begs some questioning on our part as to whether that stuff is needed...

Spring 6 is currently being developed, and this provides us with a unique window of opportunity to make these large changes in a way they will get to an benefit a large number of people.

For this version, Spring is establishing a Java 17 baseline.

Since we'll need to change the Java baseline to 11 to support Netty 5, we might as well go the extra mile and choose **Java 17** instead.

By the time Reactor 4 is finally out next year, Java 11 will already be (close to) end of support.

We believe this is a bold move, but that it is the right move.

See the discussion in https://github.com/reactor/reactor/issues/703 around Java 17 specifically.

## Opportunity for other (smaller-scale) changes

There are other changes that could probably be done in Reactor 3, but would actually make better sense in a Gen4:
 - entirely new APIs / operators
 - grouping some operators under API groups
 - using more builder / spec patterns
 - `Message`-like API to pass data and metadata (from the `Context`)
 - new types of macro-fusion across different operators
 - graph materialization and introspection

Gen4 would also be a good opportunity to prune the codebase of all current deprecations.', 'reactions': {'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/reactor/reactor/issues/705/reactions', 'total_count': 0, '+1': 0, '-1': 0, 'laugh': 0, 'hooray': 0, 'confused': 0, 'heart': 0, 'rocket': 0, 'eyes': 0}, 'timeline_url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/reactor/reactor/issues/705/timeline', 'performed_via_github_app': None}, 'comment': {'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/reactor/reactor/issues/comments/1025989962', 'html_url': 'https://github.com/reactor/reactor/issues/705#issuecomment-1025989962', 'issue_url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/reactor/reactor/issues/705', 'id': 1025989962, 'node_id': 'IC_kwDOAJKfOs49J11K', 'user': {'login': 'JonathanGiles', 'id': 1427840, 'node_id': 'MDQ6VXNlcjE0Mjc4NDA=', 'avatar_url': 'https://avatars.githubusercontent.com/u/1427840?v=4', 'gravatar_id': '', 'url': 'https://api.github.com/users/JonathanGiles', 'html_url': 'https://github.com/JonathanGiles', 'followers_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/JonathanGiles/followers', 'following_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/JonathanGiles/following{/other_user}', 'gists_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/JonathanGiles/gists{/gist_id}', 'starred_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/JonathanGiles/starred{/owner}{/repo}', 'subscriptions_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/JonathanGiles/subscriptions', 'organizations_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/JonathanGiles/orgs', 'repos_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/JonathanGiles/repos', 'events_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/JonathanGiles/events{/privacy}', 'received_events_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/JonathanGiles/received_events', 'type': 'User', 'site_admin': False}, 'created_at': '2022-01-31T16:52:16Z', 'updated_at': '2022-01-31T16:52:16Z', 'author_association': 'NONE', 'body': "Thank you for taking community feedback and making this choice.
